Part 9

The call came the next morning, before Vikram had finished his tea.

"Bhaiya." Meena's voice, Rohan's wife, tight and fast in the way voices get when they've been holding themselves together only for the length of a phone call. "Please. Don't panic. But Rohan's been arrested."

"Arrested. For what?"

"They're saying illegal transactions. Tender bypass. False documents — all false, bhaiya, I swear on our daughter, all false. He wouldn't sign off on the Nandyal plant construction. The contractor's work, the concrete mixing ratio, Rohan caught it himself, refused the certification. Yesterday the contractor's men came to the site office. Today the police came to our house."

Vikram sat very still, phone against his ear, cup cooling in front of him.

"He took that job on his own," Meena said, quieter now, almost apologetic, as if this fact embarrassed her on his behalf. "Wouldn't let me tell you he'd applied. Wanted to clear it without anyone knowing whose brother he was."

"I know."

"Please don't tell Papa. His heart — please, bhaiya, not right now."

"I won't. I'm coming."

---

The police station smelled of old paper and stale tea, a ceiling fan turning too slowly to matter, and Rohan sitting on a bench outside the lock-up with a swollen lip he wasn't quite hiding and wasn't quite showing either.

He looked up when Vikram walked in, and something in his face did several things at once before settling on none of them.

"You didn't need to come."

"Meena called me. Not you."

"I told her not to."

"I know that too."

The sub-inspector who'd been unhurried with Meena's earlier phone calls became, within four minutes of Vikram's lawyer arriving with the right papers and the right names attached to the right calls, a considerably more helpful version of himself — tea offered, chairs pulled out, an apology delivered in the specific tone reserved for men who fear they've made an expensive mistake.

Rohan watched all of it from the bench, silent, the swelling around his lip the only part of him that had moved in the last ten minutes.

He'd been on that same bench four hours earlier, before any lawyer, before any name attached itself usefully to anything — just an engineer who wouldn't sign a document, treated exactly like every other man who couldn't sign what a policeman was told to make him sign.

Nobody had offered him tea then.

---

In the car afterward, Rohan stared out the window without speaking for most of the drive.

"Thank you," he said finally, the words arriving stiff, like something handed over reluctantly because it was owed rather than felt.

"You'd have done the same."

"Would I." Rohan said it flatly, not quite a question. "I don't have a lawyer on retainer who makes inspectors pull out chairs, Vikram."

"That's not what I meant."

"I know what you meant." Rohan looked out the window again. "Doesn't change what I saw in there."

He didn't say what he'd seen, not directly, and Vikram didn't ask him to.

But something had shifted in the younger man's face somewhere between the bench and the car, something Vikram noticed and couldn't yet name, and Rohan, for his part, spent the rest of the drive making sure his brother never saw it clearly enough to try.
